00:04:56.910 --> 00:05:02.290
Now, we are all here today
and so many of us and at 9 AM

00:05:02.290 --> 00:05:04.400
on Saturday to affirm

00:05:04.400 --> 00:05:08.390
that despite the overwhelming
visual bias of American history

00:05:08.390 --> 00:05:11.420
and media history
through our textbooks,

00:05:11.420 --> 00:05:14.550
television documentaries,
web pages and films,

00:05:14.550 --> 00:05:17.510
we insist on the
importance of sound.

00:05:17.510 --> 00:05:20.930
And the powerful and sometimes
dominant role of sound

00:05:20.930 --> 00:05:24.840
in our national life,
past and present.

00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:26.930
We are especially
interested in how sound

00:05:26.930 --> 00:05:30.020
and listening create
communities, imagined

00:05:30.020 --> 00:05:33.280
and otherwise, dominant
and subaltern.

00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:37.120
How they cultivate intimacy
and individual, regional

00:05:37.120 --> 00:05:39.930
and national identities and have

00:05:39.930 --> 00:05:43.130
and can affirm marginalized
identities.

00:05:43.130 --> 00:05:47.470
We seek to remind folks in
this visually overloaded age

00:05:47.470 --> 00:05:53.100
that radio revolutionized the
perceptual habits of a nation

00:05:53.100 --> 00:05:55.820
by bringing orality to the fore.

00:05:55.820 --> 00:05:59.370
It forever blurred the
boundaries between the private,

00:05:59.370 --> 00:06:02.970
domestic sphere and
public commercial life

00:06:02.970 --> 00:06:04.500
and political life.

00:06:04.500 --> 00:06:08.060
It made listening to
music a daily requirement

00:06:08.060 --> 00:06:09.840
for millions of Americans.

00:06:09.840 --> 00:06:13.530
Even after TV, radio
remained a thriving cultural

00:06:13.530 --> 00:06:15.420
and political force.

00:06:15.420 --> 00:06:19.760
We are also here to insist
that yes, radio matters,

00:06:19.760 --> 00:06:24.730
radio history matters, but
also history itself matters.

00:06:24.730 --> 00:06:26.600
With all of the interest
in media

00:06:26.600 --> 00:06:31.080
and communication studies
today, in the uses and impact

00:06:31.080 --> 00:06:33.320
of big data, social media,

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:35.740
everything in our
digital environment,

00:06:35.740 --> 00:06:40.070
presentism is getting a
pretty big grip on our field.

00:06:40.070 --> 00:06:42.660
And media history
is being minimized.

00:06:42.660 --> 00:06:44.630
I think we should challenge this

00:06:44.630 --> 00:06:49.220
and championing radio history
remains an ongoing mission.

00:06:49.220 --> 00:06:52.920
And we are at an
interesting juncture here.

00:06:52.920 --> 00:06:57.500
Who would've thought five years
ago that listening to stories,

00:06:57.500 --> 00:07:01.880
mysteries, politics without
images would reemerge

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:04.800
as a popular and
widespread practice.

00:07:04.800 --> 00:07:09.440
And then Serial happened in
2014 and it became a word

00:07:09.440 --> 00:07:12.270
of mouth phenomenon
across generations.

00:07:12.270 --> 00:07:15.920
I learned about Serial
from 20 somethings.

00:07:15.920 --> 00:07:18.510
And now, we have
multiple true crime

00:07:18.510 --> 00:07:21.780
and murder mystery
podcasts, political podcasts,

00:07:21.780 --> 00:07:24.860
like Pod Save America
and Love it or Leave it,

00:07:24.860 --> 00:07:28.110
journalistic podcasts
from the New York Times.

00:07:28.110 --> 00:07:31.910
Even politicians are seeking
to host their own podcasts.

00:07:31.910 --> 00:07:35.910
They are luring people into
listening and imagining again.

00:07:35.910 --> 00:07:38.050
Will these be saved as part

00:07:38.050 --> 00:07:41.730
of this distinctive national
moment, or will they evaporate

00:07:41.730 --> 00:07:46.290
into the ether, like so many
previous sound broadcasts.

00:07:46.290 --> 00:07:50.540
Everyone here knows how we
have had to be and still have

00:07:50.540 --> 00:07:55.590
to be detectives in locating
archives, audio and print some

00:07:55.590 --> 00:07:58.340
of them quite motley
and incoherent

00:07:58.340 --> 00:08:00.500
and to discover what's in them.

00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:03.490
We're learning at this gathering
how many more archives are

00:08:03.490 --> 00:08:04.790
out there.

00:08:04.790 --> 00:08:07.480
Some still being built
and preserved often

00:08:07.480 --> 00:08:09.630
by indefatigable people.

00:08:09.630 --> 00:08:13.970
Many of us in our work have
had to piece together what's

00:08:13.970 --> 00:08:16.640
in everything from like
the Paley Center for Media

00:08:16.640 --> 00:08:20.540
to Chicago's museum of Broadcast
Communications, to the Library

00:08:20.540 --> 00:08:23.550
of American Broadcasting at
the University of Maryland,

00:08:23.550 --> 00:08:25.810
to the Pacifica Radio Archives.

00:08:25.810 --> 00:08:27.180
There is so many
more to, of course,

00:08:27.180 --> 00:08:29.370
the Recorded Sound Research
Center here at the Library

00:08:29.370 --> 00:08:32.000
of Congress, and many more.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:35.980
Many of these, though not
all, privilege the networks

00:08:35.980 --> 00:08:37.940
and a centralized
national history.

00:08:37.940 --> 00:08:41.910
So, many recordings from local
stations were thrown away.

00:08:41.910 --> 00:08:46.010
And yet, how many might still
be moldering in boxes somewhere,

00:08:46.010 --> 00:08:48.970
probably in someone's garage.

00:08:48.970 --> 00:08:50.920
Now, to tell our stories,

00:08:50.920 --> 00:08:53.590
these archives were
just the beginning.

00:08:53.590 --> 00:08:55.990
Radio and sound historians
have had

00:08:55.990 --> 00:08:59.060
to contextualize audio archives

00:08:59.060 --> 00:09:02.380
within the broader
printed historical record.

00:09:02.380 --> 00:09:05.480
And this is almost
always an archive we have

00:09:05.480 --> 00:09:07.570
to build ourselves.

00:09:07.570 --> 00:09:12.390
How many of us have in our
offices, basements, attics,

00:09:12.390 --> 00:09:15.860
garages, our own radio archives?

00:09:15.860 --> 00:09:20.360
Journalistic articles, copies of
fan mail, cassettes, interviews

00:09:20.360 --> 00:09:23.680
and the like that we
have had to put together

00:09:23.680 --> 00:09:26.020
and we can't bear to part with.

00:09:26.020 --> 00:09:30.510
These DIY archives help
us establish timelines,

00:09:30.510 --> 00:09:33.120
assessed impact and
controversies

00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:36.830
and helped us see the growing
intertextuality among sound,

00:09:36.830 --> 00:09:38.360
image and print.

00:09:38.360 --> 00:09:42.950
These too are part of the
radio archives infrastructure.

00:09:42.950 --> 00:09:46.620
Should part of our preservation
task be amalgamating these

00:09:46.620 --> 00:09:49.500
archives that we
each have built?

00:09:49.500 --> 00:09:52.610
Probably if we did, it
would fill the entire floor

00:09:52.610 --> 00:09:54.540
of this building.

00:09:54.540 --> 00:10:00.840
Part of our preservation
task, also have to do

00:10:00.840 --> 00:10:04.340
with preserving the oral
histories we collected.

00:10:04.340 --> 00:10:06.830
The audio interviews we've done.

00:10:06.830 --> 00:10:11.080
I have at least two huge file
drawers filled with my archive

00:10:11.080 --> 00:10:13.770
for Listening In,
merely 20 years old now

00:10:13.770 --> 00:10:16.150
and I cannot bear
to throw it away.

00:10:16.150 --> 00:10:17.870
Who would take them?

00:10:17.870 --> 00:10:19.270
Where would they go?

00:10:19.270 --> 00:10:21.370
[Inaudible].

00:10:21.370 --> 00:10:23.470
[Laughter].

00:10:23.470 --> 00:10:27.110
So, where do, where does radio
studies seem to be going?

00:10:27.110 --> 00:10:29.830
First, of course,
is the decentering

00:10:29.830 --> 00:10:34.040
of the National Network story
and the golden age of radio.

00:10:34.040 --> 00:10:38.350
And the exhuming and preserving
of local and regional histories.

00:10:38.350 --> 00:10:40.860
This conference, recent research

00:10:40.860 --> 00:10:43.980
and the archives still
emerging document the crucial

00:10:43.980 --> 00:10:48.200
and massively underappreciated
role that radio, especially,

00:10:48.200 --> 00:10:51.800
but not solely community and
listener supported radio,

00:10:51.800 --> 00:10:56.280
played in addressing and giving
voice to marginalized groups,

00:10:56.280 --> 00:11:00.970
including the LGBTQ community
as early as the 1970's,

00:11:00.970 --> 00:11:04.900
indigenous first nations
communities, Chicano and Latinos

00:11:04.900 --> 00:11:06.570
and African Americans.

00:11:06.570 --> 00:11:10.340
More histories can and need to
be written about the connections

00:11:10.340 --> 00:11:14.050
between such stations, this
kind of radio listening,

00:11:14.050 --> 00:11:17.460
community building and
political activism.

00:11:17.460 --> 00:11:19.630
Also, we have to remember

00:11:19.630 --> 00:11:24.090
that in 1971 the FCC issued
its primer on ascertainment

00:11:24.090 --> 00:11:27.030
of community problems
by broadcast applicants,

00:11:27.030 --> 00:11:32.020
what a euphonious title, which
gave detailed instructions

00:11:32.020 --> 00:11:34.950
on how to determine
community needs.

00:11:34.950 --> 00:11:38.710
Stations had to develop
an ascertainment procedure

00:11:38.710 --> 00:11:40.470
that would document
the demographics

00:11:40.470 --> 00:11:44.220
of the stations market, identify
what were called significant

00:11:44.220 --> 00:11:47.800
community groups and
hold meetings with them

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:51.420
to discuss community needs
and propose programming

00:11:51.420 --> 00:11:53.380
that would meet those needs.

00:11:53.380 --> 00:11:56.770
These had to be filed
with license renewals.

00:11:56.770 --> 00:11:59.360
So, what were commercial
stations doing

00:11:59.360 --> 00:12:04.580
in the 1970's before Reagan's
FCC rescinded these rules

00:12:04.580 --> 00:12:08.440
that might also have covered and
given voice to underrepresented

00:12:08.440 --> 00:12:10.290
and marginalized groups?

00:12:10.290 --> 00:12:14.230
When we find them and we can
use these available clips

00:12:14.230 --> 00:12:18.560
to teach our students about
radios unsung role here.

00:12:18.560 --> 00:12:21.980
And this is an important
way to link our colleges

00:12:21.980 --> 00:12:24.960
and universities
commitments to diversity,

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:29.190
to teaching about previously
ignored histories that matter.

00:12:29.190 --> 00:12:34.230
And I'm stealing a line that
Kathy Battles gave me yesterday.

00:12:34.230 --> 00:12:38.070
These broadcasts with their
community building functions

00:12:38.070 --> 00:12:41.060
constitute, and this
is a quote from Kathy,

00:12:41.060 --> 00:12:42.930
the prehistory of social media.

00:12:42.930 --> 00:12:45.220
And she's totally right.

00:12:45.220 --> 00:12:48.820
That's maybe how we should
teach some of these materials.

00:12:48.820 --> 00:12:50.890
And let our colleagues
and ethnic studies,

00:12:50.890 --> 00:12:54.570
sexuality studies
and other fields know

00:12:54.570 --> 00:12:56.670
that they're out there.

00:12:56.670 --> 00:12:58.900
Another possible
future is to continue

00:12:58.900 --> 00:13:02.560
to study listening itself
from radios multiple modes

00:13:02.560 --> 00:13:05.760
of address, the phenomenology
of listening,

00:13:05.760 --> 00:13:10.680
to how we engage cognitively and
emotionally with what we hear.

00:13:10.680 --> 00:13:13.840
How do we, ourselves
as researchers,

00:13:13.840 --> 00:13:16.740
engage with audio archives?

00:13:16.740 --> 00:13:19.330
We've come a long way
in the past 30 years

00:13:19.330 --> 00:13:21.220
in developing analytical
frameworks

00:13:21.220 --> 00:13:24.830
to conceptualize the role
and impact of radio and sound

00:13:24.830 --> 00:13:28.300
on American culture, politics,
the economy and on racial,

00:13:28.300 --> 00:13:30.930
class, ethnic and
gender identities.

00:13:30.930 --> 00:13:33.630
But what would we
say our methods are?

00:13:33.630 --> 00:13:34.930
Especially once we're

00:13:34.930 --> 00:13:37.500
in the audio archives
and we're listening.

00:13:37.500 --> 00:13:41.730
For those of us who are, who
are humanities based scholars,

00:13:41.730 --> 00:13:45.220
we don't have a tradition like
our social science colleagues,

00:13:45.220 --> 00:13:48.090
in laying out in often
painstaking detail what our

00:13:48.090 --> 00:13:49.850
methods are.

00:13:49.850 --> 00:13:53.400
Yet, many of us have tried to
construct a kind of semiotics

00:13:53.400 --> 00:13:57.680
of sound as part of our methods,
which don't really exist,

00:13:57.680 --> 00:14:00.920
aren't terribly codified
and maybe can't be.

00:14:00.920 --> 00:14:04.270
Now, of course, we focused on
the content of radio broadcast,

00:14:04.270 --> 00:14:07.940
its distinctive language,
its mode of description

00:14:07.940 --> 00:14:10.360
on the development and
use of sound effects,

00:14:10.360 --> 00:14:15.490
on music as a punctuating force,
on radio voices and as gendered

00:14:15.490 --> 00:14:17.690
and raced and the like.

00:14:17.690 --> 00:14:20.550
In my own work, I sought
to develop an archeology

00:14:20.550 --> 00:14:22.630
of listening, proposing
what types

00:14:22.630 --> 00:14:25.580
of listening may have
emerged or evolved over time.

00:14:25.580 --> 00:14:30.210
And how mode of address, tone
of voice, vocal acrobatics,

00:14:30.210 --> 00:14:31.900
linguistic slapstick and the

00:14:31.900 --> 00:14:35.310
like may have shaped
broadcasting practices

00:14:35.310 --> 00:14:37.380
and listening repertoires.

00:14:37.380 --> 00:14:41.050
Now, whether what I proposed
holds up, I don't know.

00:14:41.050 --> 00:14:45.830
but sharing with each other how
we listen, what we listen for,

00:14:45.830 --> 00:14:49.010
what we believe different
sounds signify

00:14:49.010 --> 00:14:52.020
and what we think their
dominant, oppositional

00:14:52.020 --> 00:14:54.560
and negotiated readings
might be,

00:14:54.560 --> 00:14:57.730
might help elaborate our
collective understandings

00:14:57.730 --> 00:14:59.520
of the semiotics of sound,

00:14:59.520 --> 00:15:02.160
especially of radio
broadcasting.

00:15:02.160 --> 00:15:04.320
Another direction
for radio studies is

00:15:04.320 --> 00:15:09.100
of course analyzing the
phenomenon of the podcast.

00:15:09.100 --> 00:15:11.470
You can barely keep
up with them.

00:15:11.470 --> 00:15:13.890
And many are followed
by young people.

00:15:13.890 --> 00:15:16.130
What other different
modes of address?

00:15:16.130 --> 00:15:18.060
They're journalistic practices.

00:15:18.060 --> 00:15:20.820
They're presentation of
different identities.

00:15:20.820 --> 00:15:24.760
Now, I have one you might
find odd observation

00:15:24.760 --> 00:15:30.810
that distinguishes some of them
absolutely from broadcast radio.

00:15:30.810 --> 00:15:34.120
One thing about the few
podcasts I listen to, Love it

00:15:34.120 --> 00:15:38.350
or Leave it, Pod Save America,
occasionally My Favorite Murder.

00:15:38.350 --> 00:15:39.800
Do you guys know
My Favorite Murder?

00:15:39.800 --> 00:15:42.430
Okay, yeah, yeah, okay.

00:15:42.430 --> 00:15:46.750
Is the way they create intimacy
and bond with their audience,

00:15:46.750 --> 00:15:50.810
in part by relying quite
frequently on the F word,

00:15:50.810 --> 00:15:53.400
particularly as an adjective.

00:15:53.400 --> 00:15:57.100
These podcasts rely on a
combination of humor, political

00:15:57.100 --> 00:16:01.840
and social commentary and
outrage and are geared primarily

00:16:01.840 --> 00:16:05.080
to those in their 20's
and 30's, for whom,

00:16:05.080 --> 00:16:09.170
at least in my experience, the
F word is one of the more common

00:16:09.170 --> 00:16:12.950
and emphatic adjectives,
regardless of gender.

00:16:12.950 --> 00:16:16.760
And it is used to convey
anger, disgust, outrage,

00:16:16.760 --> 00:16:19.880
but also with an edge of
irreverence and humor,

00:16:19.880 --> 00:16:22.440
as in that is fucking crazy.

00:16:22.440 --> 00:16:25.810
It almost always has
nothing to do with sex

00:16:25.810 --> 00:16:30.460
and is rather an exclamatory
filler affirming defiance.

00:16:30.460 --> 00:16:33.990
This would be impossible
on broadcast radio.

00:16:33.990 --> 00:16:38.910
And its frequent use works to
create an in club of listeners

00:16:38.910 --> 00:16:41.670
who don't care about
stodgy old forms of decorum,

00:16:41.670 --> 00:16:42.970
censorship or [inaudible].

00:16:42.970 --> 00:16:47.210
These broadcasts, these podcasts
are often staged before a live

00:16:47.210 --> 00:16:50.830
audience, also to create
a sense of community.

00:16:50.830 --> 00:16:53.240
So, radio and listening
are not dead.

00:16:53.240 --> 00:16:57.040
And podcasts are bringing
this new form of engagement

00:16:57.040 --> 00:16:58.530
to a younger generation.

00:16:58.530 --> 00:17:02.730
How they create intimacy is
just one of many questions.

00:17:02.730 --> 00:17:05.150
But their affordances
are a bit different.

00:17:05.150 --> 00:17:08.530
We listen when we want
with others or alone.

00:17:08.530 --> 00:17:11.570
They are not constrained
by broadcast regulation.

00:17:11.570 --> 00:17:14.730
Knowledge of them spreads
primarily by word of mouth,

00:17:14.730 --> 00:17:17.670
which is always such
a mysterious process.

00:17:17.670 --> 00:17:19.900
How do we grasp this
new phenomenon

00:17:19.900 --> 00:17:21.800
and its generational address?

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:25.000
How are gender and race
performed on these podcasts?

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:27.610
And have they more closely
connected the voices

00:17:27.610 --> 00:17:31.070
of young women to politics,
even though Love it or Leave it

00:17:31.070 --> 00:17:34.520
and Pod Save America
are hosted by white men.

00:17:34.520 --> 00:17:37.750
And as we think about the
future of radio studies,

00:17:37.750 --> 00:17:41.610
one framework can be our
wireless imagination.

00:17:41.610 --> 00:17:44.070
How the imaginary about radio?

00:17:44.070 --> 00:17:45.590
Who the audience is?

00:17:45.590 --> 00:17:48.730
What radio was and
is meant to do?

00:17:48.730 --> 00:17:50.670
How it connects with politics

00:17:50.670 --> 00:17:53.120
and a longing still
for community?

00:17:53.120 --> 00:17:54.420
As a through line

00:17:54.420 --> 00:17:58.730
from wirelesses earliest
days up to the present.

00:17:58.730 --> 00:18:02.260
Does radio studies include
services like Spotify,

00:18:02.260 --> 00:18:05.020
Apple Radio, iTunes and Pandora?

00:18:05.020 --> 00:18:07.550
And how music listening
has changed again

00:18:07.550 --> 00:18:11.230
