00:53:48.070 --> 00:53:50.270
you know, digitization
and radio is dying.

00:53:50.270 --> 00:53:52.050
In America we're
actually pretty lucky,

00:53:52.050 --> 00:53:57.470
in that we have a shitty digital
radio system called HD radio.

00:53:57.470 --> 00:53:59.920
It is spectrally intensive.

00:53:59.920 --> 00:54:02.170
It does not provide a
qualitative improvement

00:54:02.170 --> 00:54:05.810
over analog broadcasting
and it's wholly proprietary,

00:54:05.810 --> 00:54:07.110
meaning that you actually have

00:54:07.110 --> 00:54:09.860
to pay a private
company a licensing fee

00:54:09.860 --> 00:54:11.870
to adopt the radio technology.

00:54:11.870 --> 00:54:16.490
Fortunately, the FCC back in the
early 2000's made the adoption

00:54:16.490 --> 00:54:19.620
of the digital radio
standard wholly voluntarily,

00:54:19.620 --> 00:54:22.380
wholly voluntary and
driven by the marketplace.

00:54:22.380 --> 00:54:25.270
And the marketplace has
pretty much rejected HD radio,

00:54:25.270 --> 00:54:27.020
less than 15 percent

00:54:27.020 --> 00:54:29.410
of all licensed broadcasters
have actually adopted the

00:54:29.410 --> 00:54:32.090
technology and the platform
itself has been sold

00:54:32.090 --> 00:54:34.210
from its parent company
and it's now part

00:54:34.210 --> 00:54:37.060
of a larger intellectual
property conglomerate

00:54:37.060 --> 00:54:40.840
that doesn't really care that
much about radio broadcasting.

00:54:40.840 --> 00:54:44.480
So, HD radio and the
digital transition of radio

00:54:44.480 --> 00:54:45.780
in the United States
is something

00:54:45.780 --> 00:54:48.840
that can be actively
resisted on many fronts.

00:54:48.840 --> 00:54:52.000
And I'd also kind of like to
make a plea for the analog,

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:53.590
since digital radio transition

00:54:53.590 --> 00:54:55.990
in the United States is
not working very well,

00:54:55.990 --> 00:54:57.740
there is something to be said

00:54:57.740 --> 00:55:01.410
for reclaiming analog
spectrum for community use.

00:55:01.410 --> 00:55:04.070
Analog radio is not trackable.

00:55:04.070 --> 00:55:07.650
It's not part of the panopticon,
like social media is.

00:55:07.650 --> 00:55:10.360
And for people that are
very involved in activism,

00:55:10.360 --> 00:55:13.030
that's a very useful
tactical tool

00:55:13.030 --> 00:55:15.720
and the FCC does not
have the authority,

00:55:15.720 --> 00:55:17.870
nor has it really had
the full authority

00:55:17.870 --> 00:55:21.870
to actually enforce the
broadcast license requirement.

00:55:21.870 --> 00:55:25.480
So, yesterday I was talking in
one of the panels about the fact

00:55:25.480 --> 00:55:27.970
that in the place where
I live, New York City,

00:55:27.970 --> 00:55:30.310
there are more unlicensed
FM radio stations

00:55:30.310 --> 00:55:33.820
on the air right now, than there
are licensed FM radio stations.

00:55:33.820 --> 00:55:37.380
So, those of you who are
interested in media activism

00:55:37.380 --> 00:55:41.060
and social movements, I would
strongly suggest that you look

00:55:41.060 --> 00:55:42.510
at radio as a mechanism

00:55:42.510 --> 00:55:45.160
for tactical organization
and communication.

00:55:45.160 --> 00:55:49.040
And it's a fairly simple risk
assessment to do and it actually

00:55:49.040 --> 00:55:53.710
in my view has been a key
component to the revitalization

00:55:53.710 --> 00:55:56.190
of radio as a community
building exercise

00:55:56.190 --> 00:55:57.660
and I think that's
going to continue

00:55:57.660 --> 00:55:59.390
for the foreseeable future.

