your credits this way, right?

01:17:59.600 --> 01:18:02.640
So, it's, it's a
whole sort of work

01:18:02.640 --> 01:18:04.310
to legitimize the
language again,

01:18:04.310 --> 01:18:08.360
as again a contemporary language
and a language that's around us.

01:18:08.360 --> 01:18:14.350
So, the radio show was
a wonderful way for them

01:18:14.350 --> 01:18:16.520
to get together [foreign
language] got together.

01:18:16.520 --> 01:18:18.600
And [foreign language] had
already this wonderful radio

01:18:18.600 --> 01:18:23.310
experience, built the studio
that you see now in a basement

01:18:23.310 --> 01:18:24.610
of a building in the Bronx.

01:18:24.610 --> 01:18:28.890
And this is how Kichwa Hatari
begins, by just doing it

01:18:28.890 --> 01:18:30.310
and bringing the
community together.

01:18:30.310 --> 01:18:34.070
And they broadcast in Spanish
and Quechua, sometimes in Kichwa

01:18:34.070 --> 01:18:35.380
and sometimes in
English depending

01:18:35.380 --> 01:18:37.470
on who their guests are.

01:18:37.470 --> 01:18:40.530
So, as a programming of the
Folklife Festival last year,

01:18:40.530 --> 01:18:43.410
we really wanted to bring
these kind of initiatives

01:18:43.410 --> 01:18:46.140
and this kind of
work to them all.

01:18:46.140 --> 01:18:48.380
So, we built a little
station called,

01:18:48.380 --> 01:18:52.580
during our program
called On the Move.

01:18:52.580 --> 01:18:54.970
We were talking about migration
in the United States as part

01:18:54.970 --> 01:18:56.740
of a 50th anniversary.

01:18:56.740 --> 01:19:00.450
We had a media production
setup, really, really barebones.

01:19:00.450 --> 01:19:02.530
I don't know if you've been to
the festival, but we have it

01:19:02.530 --> 01:19:04.290
on the mall and then
take it down.

01:19:04.290 --> 01:19:05.860
So, there are no hard walls.

01:19:05.860 --> 01:19:09.820
It's all just tarp
and two by fours.

01:19:09.820 --> 01:19:13.420
So, we build this media
studio on the mall.

01:19:13.420 --> 01:19:14.990
And we invited Kichwa Hatari

01:19:14.990 --> 01:19:17.230
to be our resident
media collective.

01:19:17.230 --> 01:19:19.900
So, they basically, when
we were planning this,

01:19:19.900 --> 01:19:21.430
I was thinking how are
you going to do this

01:19:21.430 --> 01:19:23.580
and when they told me the
activities they were thinking,

01:19:23.580 --> 01:19:26.310
I was like you're
basically bringing the studio

01:19:26.310 --> 01:19:27.760
onto the mall, right?

01:19:27.760 --> 01:19:30.540
So, that's what they did.

01:19:30.540 --> 01:19:33.660
So, this was them intervening
this blackboard that we put.

01:19:33.660 --> 01:19:35.830
They brought the [foreign
language], the flag.

01:19:35.830 --> 01:19:38.620
And, of course, we
also had other programs

01:19:38.620 --> 01:19:41.210
with the local Andean
community, which is huge here

01:19:41.210 --> 01:19:43.820
around the D.C. Virginia area.

01:19:43.820 --> 01:19:46.960
So, thinking about the people I
was bringing, I was very excited

01:19:46.960 --> 01:19:48.260
to think that there
would be all these,

01:19:48.260 --> 01:19:50.080
all these cross references.

01:19:50.080 --> 01:19:51.380
So, Kichwa Hatari ends

01:19:51.380 --> 01:19:53.350
up interviewing the
[foreign language] team

01:19:53.350 --> 01:19:55.390
or the dance troupe
that we brought

01:19:55.390 --> 01:19:58.110
of different Bolivian
[inaudible] dancers.

01:19:58.110 --> 01:20:00.280
And in Quechua, in
Kichwa, right,

01:20:00.280 --> 01:20:03.620
depending on who they were
bringing, mostly Quechua,

01:20:03.620 --> 01:20:06.070
interviewing a local
DJ who's Bolivian,

01:20:06.070 --> 01:20:08.190
whose grandfather spoke Quechua.

01:20:08.190 --> 01:20:10.340
And just producing these
new relationships and they

01:20:10.340 --> 01:20:13.240
like this idea of the
popup so much that.

01:20:13.240 --> 01:20:14.540
We called it the mixing room.

01:20:14.540 --> 01:20:16.630
That's what this little
space that you see behind.

01:20:16.630 --> 01:20:17.930
We call that the mixing room.

01:20:17.930 --> 01:20:20.740
And it was an open air studio
and they like this idea so much

01:20:20.740 --> 01:20:23.180
that they're now doing this
in other festivals and events.

01:20:23.180 --> 01:20:27.160
This was kind of the first
time they took the studio out.

01:20:27.160 --> 01:20:31.510
So, they have a page on the
Smithsonian Folklife website.

01:20:31.510 --> 01:20:33.030
You can go visit it and
learn a little bit more

01:20:33.030 --> 01:20:34.970
about their work.

01:20:34.970 --> 01:20:39.150
Another thing they did
was offer Quechua class.

01:20:39.150 --> 01:20:41.470
On the, in the bottom row

01:20:41.470 --> 01:20:45.350
in the middle you see five
[foreign language] doing an open

01:20:45.350 --> 01:20:48.380
air Quechua, Kichwa
class for the public.

01:20:48.380 --> 01:20:50.900
And we were able to get
this out and people came.

01:20:50.900 --> 01:20:52.200
They actually got an audience.

01:20:52.200 --> 01:20:54.730
We were having interviews
of the participants come

01:20:54.730 --> 01:20:56.500
through this open air studio.

01:20:56.500 --> 01:20:58.150
We have students come through.

01:20:58.150 --> 01:21:00.580
And at the end of the day,
they would just get together

01:21:00.580 --> 01:21:03.710
and do some music right there
on the mall after hours.

01:21:03.710 --> 01:21:05.940
So, they really took over the
space and this is just a way

01:21:05.940 --> 01:21:09.410
to show how, how you can bring
the liveness of radio out

01:21:09.410 --> 01:21:12.430
and into the air and consider
it in your programming.

01:21:12.430 --> 01:21:13.730
That it's not just
something that has

01:21:13.730 --> 01:21:15.630
to stay in a digital medium.

01:21:15.630 --> 01:21:17.900
You can show people the
value of this engagement

01:21:17.900 --> 01:21:20.340
and they really did a great
job by bringing things

01:21:20.340 --> 01:21:21.640
like the [foreign
language], the Andean flag.

01:21:21.640 --> 01:21:25.020
Things like brining the Quechua,
the Kichwa class methodology,

01:21:25.020 --> 01:21:28.760
by bringing the music,
by DJing on site.

01:21:28.760 --> 01:21:31.970
So, they really spilled over
their kind of usual format

01:21:31.970 --> 01:21:34.060
of two hour broadcast on Friday.

01:21:34.060 --> 01:21:38.400
And this is, this is
something that really was easy

01:21:38.400 --> 01:21:43.270
to incorporate into our thinking
around a live presentation

01:21:43.270 --> 01:21:46.750
on the mall open air
public presentation.

01:21:46.750 --> 01:21:51.270
So, they broadcast [foreign
language] every Friday six

01:21:51.270 --> 01:21:52.570
to eight.

01:21:52.570 --> 01:21:55.320
The episodes are archived on
the Kichwa Hatari website.

01:21:55.320 --> 01:21:57.840
It's in Spanish and in Quechua.

01:21:57.840 --> 01:21:59.620
Little pieces are
in English too.

01:21:59.620 --> 01:22:00.940
They have a Facebook page,

01:22:00.940 --> 01:22:02.540
where they're regularly
posting the events

01:22:02.540 --> 01:22:05.900
that they are starting to
travel in different places.

01:22:05.900 --> 01:22:08.470
So, they've been to Havana
to the [foreign language]

01:22:08.470 --> 01:22:11.250
to a conference there on radio.

01:22:11.250 --> 01:22:12.550
They're really getting
attention.

01:22:12.550 --> 01:22:14.210
And they have a Twitter
handle Kichwa Hatari.

01:22:14.210 --> 01:22:16.430
So, I just wanted to
bring up the importance

01:22:16.430 --> 01:22:18.990
of thinking outside of
just Spanish language.

01:22:18.990 --> 01:22:22.640
Spanish is a bridge to
other constituencies.

01:22:22.640 --> 01:22:25.120
And I think what they're
also, what Kichwa Hatari

01:22:25.120 --> 01:22:28.850
and other collectives are
doing is creating this diasp,

01:22:28.850 --> 01:22:31.330
we're bringing together this
[inaudible] of people who,

01:22:31.330 --> 01:22:32.770
because of the jobs
and the migration

01:22:32.770 --> 01:22:34.740
and sometimes documentation
status

01:22:34.740 --> 01:22:38.430
and just geographic remoteness,
they'll come together

01:22:38.430 --> 01:22:40.640
and through the radio, they're
bringing together this language

01:22:40.640 --> 01:22:43.440
community, which ends up
being a cultural community.

01:22:43.440 --> 01:22:45.110
So, that's how important
this is.

01:22:45.110 --> 01:22:49.720
And also people are using the
radio program as an entry point

01:22:49.720 --> 01:22:51.230
into language revitalization.

01:22:51.230 --> 01:22:54.010
So, by listening and hearing
Quechua and Kichwa bilingually,

01:22:54.010 --> 01:22:57.490
broadcast bilingually, people
have started to also realize

01:22:57.490 --> 01:22:59.670
that they understand or be
interested and say I want

01:22:59.670 --> 01:23:02.470
to speak better, I want
to gain fluency, right.

01:23:02.470 --> 01:23:05.160
So, this is part of the project.

01:23:05.160 --> 01:23:07.100
Their website really
explains their mission well.

01:23:07.100 --> 01:23:08.940
They talk about Andean
world view.

01:23:08.940 --> 01:23:10.240
They talk about the language.

01:23:10.240 --> 01:23:12.090
But they also talk about
the living community.

01:23:12.090 --> 01:23:14.340
And I'll be happy to
take questions later.

