01:24:43.440 --> 01:24:46.300
the fact that we too
should have a space

01:24:46.300 --> 01:24:48.910
in the airwaves of this country.

01:24:48.910 --> 01:24:50.220
We wanted to be recognized.

01:24:50.220 --> 01:24:51.850
We also wanted to express

01:24:51.850 --> 01:24:56.400
and exercise our First
Amendment rights.

01:24:56.400 --> 01:25:03.460
That's why founded Radio
Bilingue and we chose July 4th.

01:25:03.460 --> 01:25:07.690
And so, it's, it's really
important to note that date,

01:25:07.690 --> 01:25:10.290
at least for me, a cofounder,

01:25:10.290 --> 01:25:12.320
that when we founded
Radio Bilingue there were

01:25:12.320 --> 01:25:16.610
about 15 million
Latinos in the U.S.,

01:25:16.610 --> 01:25:21.310
which is about 6.5 percent
share of the U.S. population.

01:25:21.310 --> 01:25:27.910
And we're now at 58 million
in the U.S. and 18 percent

01:25:27.910 --> 01:25:29.860
of the general population.

01:25:29.860 --> 01:25:32.530
According to the [inaudible]
Trust just this week,

01:25:32.530 --> 01:25:37.370
they put out 72 percent of us
Latinos speak Spanish at home.

01:25:37.370 --> 01:25:38.780
So, I think the importance

01:25:38.780 --> 01:25:43.800
of a Spanish language media
is not something that is like,

01:25:43.800 --> 01:25:45.800
it shouldn't be anyway,
on the back burner,

01:25:45.800 --> 01:25:48.860
but rather something that
folks should pay attention to.

01:25:48.860 --> 01:25:50.160
It's a lot of folks.

01:25:50.160 --> 01:25:53.690
And in California, essentially,

01:25:53.690 --> 01:25:56.060
I don't think you can get
anything past the California

01:25:56.060 --> 01:26:00.630
Legislature now without
the pen of a Latino,

01:26:00.630 --> 01:26:04.760
because we control the Senate
and we control the Assembly.

01:26:04.760 --> 01:26:06.960
So, nothing goes through.

01:26:06.960 --> 01:26:09.280
So, that's, that's
where we've come.

01:26:09.280 --> 01:26:14.270
But I want to talk about Radio
Bilingue has played a part today

01:26:14.270 --> 01:26:18.520
in, you know, it's played
a part in the development

01:26:18.520 --> 01:26:21.180
and history particularly
of California,

01:26:21.180 --> 01:26:23.960
but, but just in general.

01:26:23.960 --> 01:26:28.700
We have the same values as
the public broadcasters.

01:26:28.700 --> 01:26:31.790
We are part of the public
broadcasting family.

01:26:31.790 --> 01:26:35.730
We believe in the integrity
of, of what we put on the air.

01:26:35.730 --> 01:26:39.360
We don't accept money
from tobacco companies

01:26:39.360 --> 01:26:42.950
or liquor companies,
or anybody who's

01:26:42.950 --> 01:26:45.290
in the AFL-CIO boycott list.

01:26:45.290 --> 01:26:49.330
We understand that our
community is vulnerable.

01:26:49.330 --> 01:26:54.430
Our, you know, the, our
core audience earns less

01:26:54.430 --> 01:26:56.340
than 35 thousand a year.

01:26:56.340 --> 01:27:00.230
Our core audience probably has

01:27:00.230 --> 01:27:04.030
like a high school
education or less.

01:27:04.030 --> 01:27:08.890
So, you know, we, that's
why we have these policies

01:27:08.890 --> 01:27:10.190
and we also don't play
[foreign language]

01:27:10.190 --> 01:27:13.300
and we don't promote
drugs or violence.

01:27:13.300 --> 01:27:18.080
And that includes
violence against women.

01:27:18.080 --> 01:27:23.220
So, and we also don't,
don't allow any of our songs

01:27:23.220 --> 01:27:27.330
to be played that in any
way degrade, you know,

01:27:27.330 --> 01:27:32.510
gays and lesbians and so
on, which is very common

01:27:32.510 --> 01:27:35.920
in commercial Spanish
language media.

01:27:35.920 --> 01:27:41.340
And so, what we do in public
affairs and we the founders

01:27:41.340 --> 01:27:46.810
from the beginning thought
the heart of our and sole

01:27:46.810 --> 01:27:48.740
of our [foreign language] or
obviously [foreign language]

01:27:48.740 --> 01:27:52.960
and so we are not
Spanish speaking only.

01:27:52.960 --> 01:27:54.260
We're bilingual.

01:27:54.260 --> 01:27:55.860
So that's why it's
Radio Bilingue.

01:27:55.860 --> 01:27:58.190
And to be correct,
actually, now it should be

01:27:58.190 --> 01:28:00.740
like Radio Multilingue,
I mean because we are

01:28:00.740 --> 01:28:05.220
in fact also broadcasting
indigenous languages

01:28:05.220 --> 01:28:09.860
like [foreign language], which
is the language of my people.

01:28:09.860 --> 01:28:11.430
I'm a [foreign language]
immigrant.

01:28:11.430 --> 01:28:16.110
And also, we also broadcast
in [foreign language]

01:28:16.110 --> 01:28:21.750
in our full power FM
station in Salinas.

01:28:21.750 --> 01:28:24.330
And so, that, that
station broadcast

01:28:24.330 --> 01:28:25.870
to the [foreign language]
population because it too

01:28:25.870 --> 01:28:28.700
within the context of
indigenous in Mexico

01:28:28.700 --> 01:28:31.530
or the Americas is among
the most vulnerable.

01:28:31.530 --> 01:28:35.470
There's only about 40 or 50
thousand [foreign language]

01:28:35.470 --> 01:28:40.310
and about five thousand
are in, within our,

01:28:40.310 --> 01:28:43.310
within a service
area in Salinas.

01:28:43.310 --> 01:28:45.280
And then, in terms of,
[foreign language],

01:28:45.280 --> 01:28:50.350
there's about three million of
us and of course our homeland is

01:28:50.350 --> 01:28:54.020
in the Northern part of the
state of [foreign language],

01:28:54.020 --> 01:28:56.330
Southern part of
[foreign language].

01:28:56.330 --> 01:28:59.120
But, anyway, in one
of our beats,

01:28:59.120 --> 01:29:03.490
our beats include [inaudible],
which is typical of,

01:29:03.490 --> 01:29:07.450
if you take out any,
how will I say, yeah,

01:29:07.450 --> 01:29:11.010
surveys of what Latinos
are interested in.

01:29:11.010 --> 01:29:12.310
We cover those.

01:29:12.310 --> 01:29:14.150
You hear about education.

01:29:14.150 --> 01:29:16.700
You hear about economic
opportunity.

01:29:16.700 --> 01:29:18.800
You hear about immigration.

01:29:18.800 --> 01:29:21.000
You talk about health access.

01:29:21.000 --> 01:29:22.350
So, we cover those beats.

01:29:22.350 --> 01:29:25.210
And, of course, we also cover
the arts and literature.

01:29:25.210 --> 01:29:27.830
And so, if you look
at immigration

01:29:27.830 --> 01:29:32.480
that has been something that
we have followed very closely

01:29:32.480 --> 01:29:34.100
for a lot of reasons, including

01:29:34.100 --> 01:29:39.220
that literally it's a
life changing situation

01:29:39.220 --> 01:29:41.250
for many of our families.

01:29:41.250 --> 01:29:46.140
Just in Fresno, the City
of Fresno and also LA,

01:29:46.140 --> 01:29:50.020
one out of five children
in LA Unified

01:29:50.020 --> 01:29:54.300
or Fresno Unified has one
or two undocumented parents.

01:29:54.300 --> 01:29:57.250
I mean, that's, you know,
that gives you a sense

01:29:57.250 --> 01:30:03.160
of the dimension of why right
now, for example, there's a lot

01:30:03.160 --> 01:30:05.950
of fear among the
Latino community.

01:30:05.950 --> 01:30:08.840
And that includes our audience.

01:30:08.840 --> 01:30:13.190
So, if you look at, looking back
at Radio Bilingue's history,

01:30:13.190 --> 01:30:17.370
we were there when we covered
the immigration debates,

01:30:17.370 --> 01:30:19.090
you know, in the mid 80's,

01:30:19.090 --> 01:30:21.300
leading to the Simpson-Rodino
Bill,

01:30:21.300 --> 01:30:25.890
which equalized some
three million folks,

01:30:25.890 --> 01:30:30.970
and which opened doors to
economic opportunities,

01:30:30.970 --> 01:30:32.920
etcetera, etcetera and
coming out of the shadows.

01:30:32.920 --> 01:30:36.760
So, Radio Bilingue provides
a daily forum, live forum.

01:30:36.760 --> 01:30:39.720
We have a talk show called
[foreign language] that began

01:30:39.720 --> 01:30:45.960
in 1995, which it literally,
it was modeled after Talk

01:30:45.960 --> 01:30:49.270
of the Nation, that was part
of National Public Radio.

01:30:49.270 --> 01:30:52.060
I think that was abandoned
like three or four years ago.

01:30:52.060 --> 01:30:54.740
But, so, you get
a sense of that.

01:30:54.740 --> 01:30:58.080
But, talk in Spanish,
particularly for our families,

01:30:58.080 --> 01:31:00.620
is really, really critical.

01:31:00.620 --> 01:31:04.560
It's something that, you
know, it's a way for people

01:31:04.560 --> 01:31:07.560
to communicate, to
learn, etcetera.

01:31:07.560 --> 01:31:14.530
And so, we also covered in
the 90's the backlash in some

01:31:14.530 --> 01:31:17.850
of the places like in the
Midwest against the migration

01:31:17.850 --> 01:31:21.830
of Mexicans and Latinos moving
into particularly the midwest.

01:31:21.830 --> 01:31:25.220
So, we cover that and of course,
it's not just the Midwest.

01:31:25.220 --> 01:31:31.890
California, Pete Wilson, and,
you know, and his, you know,

01:31:31.890 --> 01:31:35.430
folks like him who pushed
for literally a proposal

01:31:35.430 --> 01:31:38.610
and the proposal went
beyond that, a proposition

01:31:38.610 --> 01:31:43.290
that effectively, you know,
got rid of, proposed to get rid

01:31:43.290 --> 01:31:45.480
of services for the
undocumented.

01:31:45.480 --> 01:31:47.520
Eventually, it lost
in the courts.

