So, I think we understood that.

02:18:01.430 --> 02:18:04.240
So, part of this collection

02:18:04.240 --> 02:18:07.520
and the impetus behind it
was the collecting forces

02:18:07.520 --> 02:18:11.420
of our human rights archive,
one of our collecting centers.

02:18:11.420 --> 02:18:14.390
Duke, the Rubenstein
Library at Duke,

02:18:14.390 --> 02:18:18.530
the Special Collections
Library, wants more and more

02:18:18.530 --> 02:18:20.630
to be seen an as
activists library.

02:18:20.630 --> 02:18:24.790
And this was really, really a
good example of a collection

02:18:24.790 --> 02:18:27.000
that we could sink
our teeth into.

02:18:27.000 --> 02:18:30.920
But it also came smack up
against the culture at Duke,

02:18:30.920 --> 02:18:34.730
which, you know, is a
traditional research center,

02:18:34.730 --> 02:18:37.820
American research library.

02:18:37.820 --> 02:18:39.120
It's very traditional.

02:18:39.120 --> 02:18:43.400
It wants to be an activist
library, but it also really hues

02:18:43.400 --> 02:18:45.820
to the lines of standards,
which is great.

02:18:45.820 --> 02:18:50.030
It really, we really use a
lot of what's called NPLP,

02:18:50.030 --> 02:18:52.620
which is more product,
less process

02:18:52.620 --> 02:18:55.050
in our, in our archiving.

02:18:55.050 --> 02:18:57.840
And so, the idea
of spending a lot

02:18:57.840 --> 02:19:00.070
of time doing item
level description

02:19:00.070 --> 02:19:05.400
on audio was not something that
I think a lot of the people sort

02:19:05.400 --> 02:19:09.190
in the leadership were
prepared for going forward.

02:19:09.190 --> 02:19:12.710
So, we had some challenges
early on there.

02:19:12.710 --> 02:19:18.650
And the, the needs of the
collection really sort

02:19:18.650 --> 02:19:21.150
of really brought those
challenges into relief.

02:19:21.150 --> 02:19:22.490
This was a collection

02:19:22.490 --> 02:19:26.420
that needed multilingual
description for accessibility.

02:19:26.420 --> 02:19:29.790
That meant that we had to have
playback of the entire file

02:19:29.790 --> 02:19:32.600
that we got back from
a cutting corporation,

02:19:32.600 --> 02:19:33.900
which was the company

02:19:33.900 --> 02:19:36.760
that digitized the tapes
and did a great job.

02:19:36.760 --> 02:19:39.940
And that was actually
the easy part for us.

02:19:39.940 --> 02:19:42.920
We needed an understanding
of the context

02:19:42.920 --> 02:19:44.600
of the audio's creation.

02:19:44.600 --> 02:19:50.950
And this was really important to
really make sensible metadata.

02:19:50.950 --> 02:19:54.610
And really most of
all an understanding

02:19:54.610 --> 02:19:58.620
of the absolute importance
of Haitian Creole as used

02:19:58.620 --> 02:20:03.030
by the station, because it was
revolutionary for its time.

02:20:03.030 --> 02:20:06.650
They were the first media outlet
in Haiti to use Haitian Creole,

02:20:06.650 --> 02:20:10.620
which was the language
of the people.

02:20:10.620 --> 02:20:17.270
And in processing the
collection and working with it,

02:20:17.270 --> 02:20:21.290
that is really more and
more has become, in my mind,

02:20:21.290 --> 02:20:23.320
the driving force
of the collection

02:20:23.320 --> 02:20:28.090
and its continued importance,
its political importance

02:20:28.090 --> 02:20:31.830
to the people of
Haiti, its importance

02:20:31.830 --> 02:20:34.280
as it was used by the station.

02:20:34.280 --> 02:20:37.010
The language that
the station used.

02:20:37.010 --> 02:20:38.570
The way they used the language.

02:20:38.570 --> 02:20:40.350
They went a long way
towards making parts

02:20:40.350 --> 02:20:42.370
of that language concrete.

02:20:42.370 --> 02:20:47.430
And so, really understanding the
collection is an understanding

02:20:47.430 --> 02:20:49.110
of Haitian Creole.

02:20:49.110 --> 02:20:51.380
So, that required
a lot of expertise,

02:20:51.380 --> 02:20:55.440
which we got very lucky and
were able to hire Laura Wagner

02:20:55.440 --> 02:20:58.760
to do the processing
of the collection.

02:20:58.760 --> 02:21:04.620
So, Laura sits and she listens
to audio and she describes it.

02:21:04.620 --> 02:21:08.830
And she bring to bear on that
audio a cultural expertise

02:21:08.830 --> 02:21:13.070
and cultural context
and history of Haiti

02:21:13.070 --> 02:21:14.630
that is really just outstanding.

02:21:14.630 --> 02:21:20.410
And there are a lot of
problems regarding especially

02:21:20.410 --> 02:21:22.640
authorities, controlled
vocabularies.

02:21:22.640 --> 02:21:26.230
LC headings don't really do
for these kinds of collections.

02:21:26.230 --> 02:21:29.710
LC headings are not
really tuned to.

02:21:29.710 --> 02:21:34.160
Or I should say that
maybe they have all that,

02:21:34.160 --> 02:21:38.200
they bring all the
cultural baggage of sort

02:21:38.200 --> 02:21:40.070
of mainstream America
with it, right?

02:21:40.070 --> 02:21:41.660
So, they don't really think

02:21:41.660 --> 02:21:45.430
about how place names might
be constructed in Haiti.

02:21:45.430 --> 02:21:48.490
They might not think about how
personal names are constructed

02:21:48.490 --> 02:21:49.790
in Haiti.

02:21:49.790 --> 02:21:53.670
They might not think about the
way that certain events happened

02:21:53.670 --> 02:21:55.270
or the way that certain
events happened might be

02:21:55.270 --> 02:21:58.850
through the lens of an
American imperialism.

02:21:58.850 --> 02:22:04.250
So, in processing the collection
and wanting to apply, you know,

02:22:04.250 --> 02:22:06.690
authorities and controlled
vocabularies

02:22:06.690 --> 02:22:09.820
so records could be searched
effectively across collections.

02:22:09.820 --> 02:22:12.440
It was a real challenge for us.

02:22:12.440 --> 02:22:17.390
And we do a lot of
basically local,

02:22:17.390 --> 02:22:22.940
local controlled vocabulary
in describing the collection.

02:22:22.940 --> 02:22:24.990
We have database issues with it.

02:22:24.990 --> 02:22:26.990
As a trilingual collection.

02:22:26.990 --> 02:22:30.930
Well, this actually goes
back to the importance

02:22:30.930 --> 02:22:34.110
of the Haitian Creole, but the.

02:22:34.110 --> 02:22:36.780
We started out just using a
relational database to try

02:22:36.780 --> 02:22:38.690
to wrangle everything together.

02:22:38.690 --> 02:22:41.930
But the problem with that was we
had difficulty copying records,

02:22:41.930 --> 02:22:43.230
which is really important

02:22:43.230 --> 02:22:48.360
when you're creating 51 hundred
records or 53 hundred records.

02:22:48.360 --> 02:22:52.490
And the other, the other issue
was that we needed to be able

02:22:52.490 --> 02:22:56.050
to get the information out
into a flat spreadsheet,

02:22:56.050 --> 02:22:58.030
which we weren't sure we could
do by the end of the project.

02:22:58.030 --> 02:22:59.470
So, we went ahead and
ported the database

02:22:59.470 --> 02:23:00.770
out to a flat spreadsheet.

02:23:00.770 --> 02:23:02.950
Well that spreadsheet
because the metadata has

02:23:02.950 --> 02:23:07.140
to be trilingual, has
over 100 fields in it.

02:23:07.140 --> 02:23:13.080
And to then ingest that into a
developing digital repository,

02:23:13.080 --> 02:23:16.710
has its own set of
complications.

02:23:16.710 --> 02:23:20.430
Amidst all of this, we have
to remain very flexible

02:23:20.430 --> 02:23:24.590
and very live in our approach to
how we process the collection.

02:23:24.590 --> 02:23:27.200
Laura, as brilliant as she
is, can't do it all on her own

02:23:27.200 --> 02:23:29.070
in the time that
we have to do it.

02:23:29.070 --> 02:23:32.260
So we have to try to find other
people with similar talents,

02:23:32.260 --> 02:23:35.060
the language skills, to
be able to help us on it.

02:23:35.060 --> 02:23:36.940
Well, you can imagine
that that population

02:23:36.940 --> 02:23:39.480
at Duke University
is fairly small.

02:23:39.480 --> 02:23:41.560
And we like to use
students when possible,

02:23:41.560 --> 02:23:43.360
because it keeps our costs down,

02:23:43.360 --> 02:23:45.260
it gives the students
experience.

02:23:45.260 --> 02:23:47.540
And in fact, we've
had some great success

02:23:47.540 --> 02:23:48.840
with some of our students.

02:23:48.840 --> 02:23:50.560
But students graduate.

02:23:50.560 --> 02:23:56.390
And so. And Duke has a hard time
hiring outside the university.

02:23:56.390 --> 02:23:59.200
We actually just got through
a whole process of trying

02:23:59.200 --> 02:24:02.270
to rehire a student
after she graduated,

02:24:02.270 --> 02:24:05.110
which set the project back
probably several months.

02:24:05.110 --> 02:24:07.210
We've just learned that we
can actually rehire her,

02:24:07.210 --> 02:24:09.990
but it took us four
months to do it.

02:24:09.990 --> 02:24:13.460
Duke is a large ship,
it's very powerful.

02:24:13.460 --> 02:24:14.760
It's well resourced.

02:24:14.760 --> 02:24:17.060
But it's very slow to turn.

02:24:17.060 --> 02:24:20.150
And so, we want, within
the archive, though,

02:24:20.150 --> 02:24:22.430
we want to make good on
that activists promise.

02:24:22.430 --> 02:24:25.040
And we want to be able to
say we can do these kinds

02:24:25.040 --> 02:24:26.910
of collections because
they're important.

02:24:26.910 --> 02:24:28.210
And they're.

02:24:28.210 --> 02:24:31.750
I told Michele Montas this
the other week when I saw her,

02:24:31.750 --> 02:24:33.560
as I had told her
before, that I really felt

02:24:33.560 --> 02:24:35.490
like this was the most
important collection I'll work

02:24:35.490 --> 02:24:37.930
on in my lifetime and my career.

02:24:37.930 --> 02:24:40.380
And I really truly believe that.

02:24:40.380 --> 02:24:42.620
And this is a collection where
I don't even understand the

02:24:42.620 --> 02:24:44.420
content when I listen to it.

02:24:44.420 --> 02:24:48.010
But the description is going
to make that more accessible

02:24:48.010 --> 02:24:51.110
to all of us in the end.

02:24:51.110 --> 02:24:52.580
And in our next steps, we hope

02:24:52.580 --> 02:24:57.000
that we can go beyond our
repository, which is very useful

02:24:57.000 --> 02:24:58.630
if you're a researcher
in the U.S.,

02:24:58.630 --> 02:25:00.820
but is less so when
you're in Haiti.

02:25:00.820 --> 02:25:03.630
And we want to actually
digitally repatriate it,

02:25:03.630 --> 02:25:09.390
hopefully if we get our grant
fulfilled, using YouTube

02:25:09.390 --> 02:25:13.030
and the internet archive to go
where Haitians are in Haiti,

02:25:13.030 --> 02:25:15.360
because that's where they are.

02:25:15.360 --> 02:25:17.530
And to us, that's our,
that's our frontier.

02:25:17.530 --> 02:25:20.350
To push an academic library
to actually use that resource

02:25:20.350 --> 02:25:23.900
in such a way that it's
effective is really our

02:25:23.900 --> 02:25:25.200
next step.

02:25:25.200 --> 02:25:26.680
And luckily we have
the rights clearances

02:25:26.680 --> 02:25:27.980
to be able to do that.

02:25:27.980 --> 02:25:32.190
So. That's a thumbnail of
the work on Radio Haiti.

