02:26:01.630 --> 02:26:05.450
Thank you very much, Alejandra,
for the invitation to talk

02:26:05.450 --> 02:26:07.120
with you, be on the panel.

02:26:07.120 --> 02:26:08.790
Thanks also to Josh Shepard

02:26:08.790 --> 02:26:10.670
and the Radio Preservation
Task Force

02:26:10.670 --> 02:26:12.400
for having their
conference this year.

02:26:12.400 --> 02:26:16.860
And giving us the opportunity
to speak with everyone.

02:26:16.860 --> 02:26:18.750
So, this morning I'm
going to talk a little bit

02:26:18.750 --> 02:26:23.220
about a collection that we
have in the Special Collections

02:26:23.220 --> 02:26:27.980
of a Latin American Library
at Tulane University.

02:26:27.980 --> 02:26:29.280
It's called the [foreign
language] collection

02:26:29.280 --> 02:26:32.310
of Cuban American Radionovelas.

02:26:32.310 --> 02:26:37.710
The collections measures
630 linear feet of material,

02:26:37.710 --> 02:26:41.280
the bulk of which
are audio tapes.

02:26:41.280 --> 02:26:46.350
And in fact, the collection
measures approximately,

02:26:46.350 --> 02:26:49.320
in terms of the audio
series its little

02:26:49.320 --> 02:26:52.260
under nine thousand
individual tapes.

02:26:52.260 --> 02:26:56.620
This is quarter inch polyester
audio tape on seven inch reels.

02:26:56.620 --> 02:26:58.910
And that's probably
represents close

02:26:58.910 --> 02:27:03.010
to three thousand 600
hours of audio recordings.

02:27:03.010 --> 02:27:06.740
The tapes actually, this,
they represent the library

02:27:06.740 --> 02:27:08.810
of radio program masters
that were produced

02:27:08.810 --> 02:27:12.370
by Americas Productions
Incorporated or API.

02:27:12.370 --> 02:27:16.320
This is a company that was
based out of Miami, Florida.

02:27:16.320 --> 02:27:20.690
It was founded in 1961
by [foreign language].

02:27:20.690 --> 02:27:24.800
Now, prior to, prior to
the 1959 Cuban Revolution,

02:27:24.800 --> 02:27:28.380
Cuba was a major producer
or radio programming,

02:27:28.380 --> 02:27:30.020
supplying as much
as a 75 percent

02:27:30.020 --> 02:27:32.140
of the canned radio programs
that were distributed

02:27:32.140 --> 02:27:34.330
to stations throughout
Latin America.

02:27:34.330 --> 02:27:38.570
That all, well that was
significantly impacted

02:27:38.570 --> 02:27:41.410
by the 59 revolution.

02:27:41.410 --> 02:27:44.420
And it also meant the
end to [inaudible] career

02:27:44.420 --> 02:27:48.660
as a public relations
man in Havana.

02:27:48.660 --> 02:27:52.510
So, after the revolution,
he resettled in Miami,

02:27:52.510 --> 02:27:54.680
as did much of the
talent that existed

02:27:54.680 --> 02:27:57.420
in Cuba prior to the revolution.

02:27:57.420 --> 02:28:00.970
The people who actually helped
to produce these radio programs.

02:28:00.970 --> 02:28:04.870
So the actors, the actresses,
directors, script writers,

02:28:04.870 --> 02:28:07.090
musicians, technicians.

02:28:07.090 --> 02:28:11.120
Many of these folks
resettled in Miami after 1959.

02:28:11.120 --> 02:28:13.600
And so, what [inaudible] was
able to do was actually fill

02:28:13.600 --> 02:28:17.900
that industry void for
programming production

02:28:17.900 --> 02:28:22.360
by founding API and by
making use of the talent

02:28:22.360 --> 02:28:26.600
that had pooled there
in Miami after 1959.

02:28:26.600 --> 02:28:33.050
Now, the company kind of began
its first couple years producing

02:28:33.050 --> 02:28:35.560
very pointed anticommunist
programs

02:28:35.560 --> 02:28:37.140
for the U.S. government,

02:28:37.140 --> 02:28:39.660
a number of which were
commissioned by Voice of America

02:28:39.660 --> 02:28:42.280
for broadcast back to Cuba.

02:28:42.280 --> 02:28:46.330
But, what [inaudible]
found was that he,

02:28:46.330 --> 02:28:48.880
in order to keep his
company commercially viable,

02:28:48.880 --> 02:28:52.200
he was going to have to
kind of shift the focus

02:28:52.200 --> 02:28:54.550
of the production of programs.

02:28:54.550 --> 02:28:58.090
And so, in 1963 he kind
of put the resources

02:28:58.090 --> 02:29:00.080
of the company towards
producing what he called

02:29:00.080 --> 02:29:01.460
pure entertainment.

02:29:01.460 --> 02:29:03.490
And so, this was going
to be programming

02:29:03.490 --> 02:29:07.350
that was more prodemocracy,
pro-capitalist in nature.

02:29:07.350 --> 02:29:11.710
Something that one of our
colleagues mentioned yesterday

02:29:11.710 --> 02:29:14.220
in one of the Cold
War sessions kind

02:29:14.220 --> 02:29:16.110
of propaganda as entertainment.

02:29:16.110 --> 02:29:18.210
And so, the idea was that
these would be programs

02:29:18.210 --> 02:29:20.790
that he could actually
license to stations

02:29:20.790 --> 02:29:23.000
and they would be able
to broadcast them,

02:29:23.000 --> 02:29:24.300
because they weren't

02:29:24.300 --> 02:29:28.240
so outwardly obviously
anticommunist.

02:29:28.240 --> 02:29:33.700
But, these were, the programming
were primarily Radionovelas

02:29:33.700 --> 02:29:36.070
or radio dramas,
radio soap operas.

02:29:36.070 --> 02:29:38.510
But they also included
mystery and suspense shows.

02:29:38.510 --> 02:29:39.850
They did informationals.

02:29:39.850 --> 02:29:41.370
They did comedy programs.

02:29:41.370 --> 02:29:43.080
They did variety programs.

02:29:43.080 --> 02:29:44.570
So, there's a whole
range of programming

02:29:44.570 --> 02:29:47.200
that they were producing
in this short stretch

02:29:47.200 --> 02:29:50.220
between 1963 and 1970.

02:29:50.220 --> 02:29:51.890
And they licensed the programs

02:29:51.890 --> 02:29:54.450
to stations throughout
Latin America,

02:29:54.450 --> 02:29:56.110
but also more importantly

02:29:56.110 --> 02:29:59.200
to the burgeoning
Spanish speaking audiences

02:29:59.200 --> 02:30:04.020
in the United States and to
Spanish markets in Europe.

02:30:04.020 --> 02:30:06.960
So, they had a wide
distribution.

02:30:06.960 --> 02:30:09.340
But I'm not really here this
morning to talk to you all

02:30:09.340 --> 02:30:13.040
about the content
of this collection.

02:30:13.040 --> 02:30:15.570
What I really wanted to
talk with you is how that,

02:30:15.570 --> 02:30:18.500
how I and my colleagues
at Tulane are trying

02:30:18.500 --> 02:30:22.390
to put these programs back
on the air, so to speak.

02:30:22.390 --> 02:30:25.040
How to convert them and
make them accessible

02:30:25.040 --> 02:30:27.780
to the public again.

02:30:27.780 --> 02:30:33.350
And the collection came to
Tulane at the end of 2004.

02:30:33.350 --> 02:30:36.770
In 2005 the Latin American
Library had a graduate student

02:30:36.770 --> 02:30:40.870
who was working to do the rough
inventory of the materials.

02:30:40.870 --> 02:30:46.020
And she was able to dub a few
of the tapes onto CD's and do a,

02:30:46.020 --> 02:30:49.650
started to a condition
assessment of the tapes.

02:30:49.650 --> 02:30:54.550
But that all abruptly came to
an end with Hurricane Katrina.

02:30:54.550 --> 02:30:58.930
The playback equipment that
the library had was destroyed

02:30:58.930 --> 02:31:00.230
by the flooding.

02:31:00.230 --> 02:31:06.020
And so, for the intervening 10
years after that, the tapes,

02:31:06.020 --> 02:31:09.020
you know, the work
couldn't continue

02:31:09.020 --> 02:31:13.550
on that project until 2015.

02:31:13.550 --> 02:31:17.970
Then, the Latin American Library
was again in a position to kind

02:31:17.970 --> 02:31:20.100
of return to that project.

02:31:20.100 --> 02:31:23.450
Also, though, the parent
library, Howard Tilton,

02:31:23.450 --> 02:31:27.080
was also, had digital
capacity by that point.

02:31:27.080 --> 02:31:29.980
So, we had, my colleague
Jeff here.

02:31:29.980 --> 02:31:33.680
We had the Tulane University
Digital Library was in place.

02:31:33.680 --> 02:31:36.460
And so, we actually had more
digital capacity to kind

02:31:36.460 --> 02:31:38.320
of come back to this project.

02:31:38.320 --> 02:31:40.570
So, was this the right moment?

02:31:40.570 --> 02:31:44.620
So, in order to begin in
2015 the first thing we had

02:31:44.620 --> 02:31:49.110
to do was establish
the copyright status.

02:31:49.110 --> 02:31:51.010
These were tapes that
were produced in kind

02:31:51.010 --> 02:31:53.110
of the donut hole of copyright.

02:31:53.110 --> 02:31:56.740
Apart from the donor agreement,
I didn't have any documentation

02:31:56.740 --> 02:32:00.350
about the multiple
different rights holders

02:32:00.350 --> 02:32:01.650
that might have been involved

02:32:01.650 --> 02:32:03.860
in the production
of these programs.

02:32:03.860 --> 02:32:05.960
And we really needed to be
sure that if we're going

02:32:05.960 --> 02:32:09.300
to digitize these
materials and put them online

02:32:09.300 --> 02:32:11.400
and make them open
access available

02:32:11.400 --> 02:32:13.410
that we were not going
to have any issues.

02:32:13.410 --> 02:32:17.040
