challenges of mold.

02:48:47.180 --> 02:48:48.930
How am I going to deal with
process of description?

02:48:48.930 --> 02:48:51.780
How am I going to, when
I have a limited budget.

02:48:51.780 --> 02:48:54.490
And the Smithsonian has a
relatively large budget,

02:48:54.490 --> 02:48:55.790
but it's going.

02:48:55.790 --> 02:48:59.920
I mean all of us are
increasingly looking to deal

02:48:59.920 --> 02:49:01.220
with the fact that our,

02:49:01.220 --> 02:49:03.940
in the cultural heritage
world our budgets are moving

02:49:03.940 --> 02:49:07.220
from a program based to a
project based foundation,

02:49:07.220 --> 02:49:09.280
meaning that for
example the Smithsonian,

02:49:09.280 --> 02:49:11.030
the Federal Government
pays essentially

02:49:11.030 --> 02:49:12.480
for buildings and staff.

02:49:12.480 --> 02:49:16.400
Everything else has
to be raised.

02:49:16.400 --> 02:49:17.700
Funds have to be raised.

02:49:17.700 --> 02:49:20.090
And I think that's true as you
listen to everyone talking today

02:49:20.090 --> 02:49:24.000
about these projects
are all grand funded.

02:49:24.000 --> 02:49:26.310
When those grants go
away, what happens?

02:49:26.310 --> 02:49:28.310
Increasingly, we're
putting things together

02:49:28.310 --> 02:49:33.590
in this ad hock one
project to another hoping

02:49:33.590 --> 02:49:36.020
that it'll all come magically
together at some point

02:49:36.020 --> 02:49:39.960
and things will be preserved
and we'll make it all work.

02:49:39.960 --> 02:49:42.160
That's a tremendous challenge.

02:49:42.160 --> 02:49:45.490
And I think everyone's kind
of underscored the fact

02:49:45.490 --> 02:49:49.040
that the answer to that is
going to be collaboration.

02:49:49.040 --> 02:49:52.240
But, I would add a couple
of different things.

02:49:52.240 --> 02:49:57.120
One -- I think of,
how should I put this?

02:49:57.120 --> 02:50:00.750
I think collecting is
always the easy part.

02:50:00.750 --> 02:50:04.760
And that the collecting really
needs to be addressed in terms

02:50:04.760 --> 02:50:08.980
of a continuum of care
that there is collecting.

02:50:08.980 --> 02:50:10.560
And that's just the start.

02:50:10.560 --> 02:50:12.500
There's processing.

02:50:12.500 --> 02:50:13.800
There's description.

02:50:13.800 --> 02:50:15.230
There's providing access.

02:50:15.230 --> 02:50:16.530
There's preservation.

02:50:16.530 --> 02:50:17.830
A

02:50:17.830 --> 02:50:19.130
And in a digital world,
preservation is an ongoing,

02:50:19.130 --> 02:50:21.490
it's really an interminable
project, right?

02:50:21.490 --> 02:50:23.470
The technology is
going to change.

02:50:23.470 --> 02:50:26.110
So, I would urge everyone
who is creating content

02:50:26.110 --> 02:50:30.410
or collecting content to
think of a collaboration

02:50:30.410 --> 02:50:32.490
within archives, not
in terms of a handoff.

02:50:32.490 --> 02:50:34.510
Okay, now it's your problem.

02:50:34.510 --> 02:50:36.900
But how do you start right
from the beginning to think

02:50:36.900 --> 02:50:39.240
about that entire
continuum of care.

02:50:39.240 --> 02:50:43.840
And realize that in many ways
that the point of acquisition

02:50:43.840 --> 02:50:46.130
by an archivists is the point
where you get the best chance

02:50:46.130 --> 02:50:48.690
of raising the money to
deal with that collection.

02:50:48.690 --> 02:50:51.570
That very often, you know,
if you give something

02:50:51.570 --> 02:50:54.510
to an archives, it is going
to go into the back of a room.

02:50:54.510 --> 02:50:55.840
It is going to be
stowed on a shelf.

02:50:55.840 --> 02:50:58.140
It is not going to be
addressed because a whole bunch

02:50:58.140 --> 02:51:00.370
of other collections are
coming in at the same time.

02:51:00.370 --> 02:51:04.460
so, I think, you know,
understanding how we might look

02:51:04.460 --> 02:51:07.990
to sharing responsibilities at
an earlier and earlier point

02:51:07.990 --> 02:51:10.100
in a continuum or a lifecycle

02:51:10.100 --> 02:51:12.110
of a collection is
really important.

02:51:12.110 --> 02:51:14.270
The other thing I would
say from the perspective

02:51:14.270 --> 02:51:17.370
of the archives is that we
have to start thinking in terms

02:51:17.370 --> 02:51:23.000
of beyond the boundaries of
the four walls of our archives.

02:51:23.000 --> 02:51:25.180
I mean, we have traditionally
thought that everything happens

02:51:25.180 --> 02:51:26.480
and this is certainly
true of the Museum

02:51:26.480 --> 02:51:28.320
of American History
and the Smithsonian.

02:51:28.320 --> 02:51:29.720
Everything happens
in that building.

02:51:29.720 --> 02:51:31.020
We collect it.

02:51:31.020 --> 02:51:32.320
We take care of it.

02:51:32.320 --> 02:51:33.620
We describe it.

02:51:33.620 --> 02:51:34.920
We interpret it.

02:51:34.920 --> 02:51:36.220
We assign meaning to these
content, to this content.

02:51:36.220 --> 02:51:39.860
And increasingly that's
not atenable proposition

02:51:39.860 --> 02:51:41.160
for all sorts of reasons.

02:51:41.160 --> 02:51:45.710
Not simply because of the budget
problems, which, you know,

02:51:45.710 --> 02:51:48.620
plague me, but also, and
the idea that, you know,

02:51:48.620 --> 02:51:50.460
we're not just sharing
information now,

02:51:50.460 --> 02:51:52.580
we're really sharing authority.

02:51:52.580 --> 02:51:55.510
It is not the role of the
Smithsonian or the Museum

02:51:55.510 --> 02:51:58.180
of American History to
interpret a collection.

02:51:58.180 --> 02:52:00.100
We want to be able to make
that collection available

02:52:00.100 --> 02:52:01.750
for other people to
interpret and other people

02:52:01.750 --> 02:52:03.510
to tell us what it means.

02:52:03.510 --> 02:52:09.010
So, looking for collaborations
that involve, I think,

02:52:09.010 --> 02:52:14.470
on one hand on the financial
scale, scale, or dealing with,

02:52:14.470 --> 02:52:16.070
or financial [inaudible]
dealing with scale.

02:52:16.070 --> 02:52:18.680
You know, not treating
problems or collections

02:52:18.680 --> 02:52:21.580
as a boutique effort that
we're going to address once

02:52:21.580 --> 02:52:22.880
and somehow raise the money.

02:52:22.880 --> 02:52:26.920
But looking for ways to share
infrastructure and enable to us

02:52:26.920 --> 02:52:28.860
to drive down the costs.

02:52:28.860 --> 02:52:31.810
Because everything you guys
have said was kind of staggering

02:52:31.810 --> 02:52:34.520
in terms of the manual
labor involved.

02:52:34.520 --> 02:52:37.100
I mean, tape by tape by tape.

02:52:37.100 --> 02:52:38.900
That's a huge cost.

02:52:38.900 --> 02:52:40.470
So, how do you address that?

02:52:40.470 --> 02:52:42.260
It's not going to
happen in one institution

02:52:42.260 --> 02:52:43.560
and then another institution

02:52:43.560 --> 02:52:46.200
and another institution all
duplicating efforts competing

02:52:46.200 --> 02:52:49.520
for the same funds, building
the same kind of infrastructure.

02:52:49.520 --> 02:52:51.660
So, those collaborations
are essential.

02:52:51.660 --> 02:52:53.500
The other thing I
would say in terms of.

02:52:53.500 --> 02:52:55.810
And that has to be driven by
the archivists and the museums

02:52:55.810 --> 02:52:57.290
and the culture of
heritage institutions.

02:52:57.290 --> 02:52:59.210
The other thing I
would say is, you know,

02:52:59.210 --> 02:53:03.600
essentially that we can,
you know, take advantage

02:53:03.600 --> 02:53:07.020
of technology in the sense
that a lot of the activities

02:53:07.020 --> 02:53:09.430
that have traditionally
been seen as archivally,

02:53:09.430 --> 02:53:12.820
archival those functions
can be shared.

02:53:12.820 --> 02:53:14.610
And should be shared,
especially in terms

02:53:14.610 --> 02:53:16.210
of description and
interpretation.

02:53:16.210 --> 02:53:19.530
There was a wonderful session on
metadata yesterday, which talked

02:53:19.530 --> 02:53:22.820
about the whole number of
different ways you can collect

02:53:22.820 --> 02:53:24.380
and aggregate metadata.

02:53:24.380 --> 02:53:28.730
And a lot of them were not
being done by the archivists.

02:53:28.730 --> 02:53:31.210
There's Google Forums,
there's aggregation.

02:53:31.210 --> 02:53:35.230
There's a wonderful project out
of Washington State run by one

02:53:35.230 --> 02:53:40.580
of my heros, Kim Withee
Macutu [assumed spelling],

02:53:40.580 --> 02:53:44.170
which is essentially a
collections management system

02:53:44.170 --> 02:53:47.370
that allows indigenous
peoples to assign values

02:53:47.370 --> 02:53:51.180
and descriptions, definitions to
content that other people hold.

02:53:51.180 --> 02:53:55.010
And the variant to that is what
something also Kim has worked

02:53:55.010 --> 02:53:56.960
on is traditional
knowledge labels,

02:53:56.960 --> 02:54:00.850
where you can essentially if
you open up your catalogue

02:54:00.850 --> 02:54:05.490
as in archives, someone else can
assign content to it as well,

02:54:05.490 --> 02:54:07.630
interpretations and metadata.

02:54:07.630 --> 02:54:10.090
And so, there's a whole
variety of technology,

02:54:10.090 --> 02:54:13.120
technological options that we
should be actively exploring.

02:54:13.120 --> 02:54:14.950
But they're going to start on
the premises that we're going

02:54:14.950 --> 02:54:17.500
to give up some of our custodial
role, we're going to give

02:54:17.500 --> 02:54:21.180
up some of our traditional
roles and responsibilities

02:54:21.180 --> 02:54:23.450
and we've just got to
share, not just information,

02:54:23.450 --> 02:54:25.900
which is what we've always
tried to do, but share authority

02:54:25.900 --> 02:54:27.800
and more importantly
share control.

02:54:27.800 --> 02:54:30.410
So, I think there are a variety
of things we could tease out.

02:54:30.410 --> 02:54:34.130
But I mean, the larger
point I was going

02:54:34.130 --> 02:54:35.810
to make is it's not going
to happen in one collection

02:54:35.810 --> 02:54:40.790
at a time, because we simply
cannot manage the costs

02:54:40.790 --> 02:54:44.350
when we look at things
like that.

